[Student "S"]
{<i>You and partner do NOT play Jacoby Transfer Bids</i>. 

With 11 points you know you want to reach game since partner has at least 15. However, you aren't sure at this point just which game to reach. If you knew partner held 3\Hs you'd choose 4\H since you would have an 8-card Major fit. On the other hand, if you knew partner had only a doubleton \H you would choose 3NT, which would probably be better. So you jump to 3\H. This bid tells partner to "Pick a Game". 

He picks 3NT.

South would play 3NT.

Click 

North plays 3NT. East leads the \SJ.

<b>North plays 3NT. East leads the \SJ.</b>

Winner count: \S 2 : \H 0 : \D 2 : \C 1 : Total = 5

Although the \D and \C suits offer the possibility for creating a winner it is evident that you really need to bring in the \Hs. By driving out the \HA you will establish the 4 winners that you need. The problem is that when you play \HQ then \HJ a good defender will hold up his \HA. You could get to dummy with the \SA and continue \Hs, but you would no longer have a sure entry to get back to those winners.

There is an almost foolproof plan. Win the first trick with your \SK (saving dummy's \SA). Lead \HQ, then \HJ, <b>OVERTAKING WITH DUMMY'S</b> \HK. Now continue the \H10 driving out the \HA. You will be able to reach the \H tricks with the \SA.

As you can see, if you don't play the \Hs as suggested West can prevent you from reaching Dummy in either \Cs or \Ds.}
[Play "W"]SJ

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "4"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "All"]
[Deal "E:A73.KJ964.KJ.QJT KQJT8.AQ.984.K96 954.T873.AQ62.75 62.52.T753.A8432"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "2H"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
1H 1S 2H pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 4, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "b22c9f5aa51b3631c30c5f3380a884518053da394c294e0d5500cc8e577f55b3"]
[Category "Practice Deals"]
[Difficulty "mixed"]
[SkillPath "practice_deals/100_miscellaneous"]
[Student "S"]
{You may not have had a problem with this opening bid, but be assured that many would. The hand meets all the requirements for an opening 1NT bid, balanced distribution and 16 points. So lots of good players would open 1NT. However, there is the question of the 5-card Major. Another group of good players don't open 1NT when their hand contains a 5-card Major.

So let us agree that either could be right and say that you chose 1\H. South overcalls 1\S, partner says 2\H and you pass.

East plays 2\H. South leads the \SK.

<b>East plays 2\H. South leads the \SK.</b>

Losers: \S 2 : \H 2 : \D 0 : \C 2 : Total = 6

You might get lucky in the trump suit and only lose one trick, but you can't count on it. Dummy's \D suit has two extra winners, but there is the problem of transportation. By the time you get to enjoy those two winners you might have already lost six tricks.

One thing should be crystal clear. If you now lead a trump the defenders will win and cash 2 \Ss. You can avoid this by waiting on the trumps and playing \DK, then overtake the \DJ with dummy's \DQ. Then play \DA and discard a \S. Now from dummy you can lead a \H and perhaps play your \HK but even if it loses you will still make the contract.

It shouldn't have come as a surprise that South held both \H A Q, after all he is the one who overcalled.

Make sure you visualize how the play would have gone if you had played a trump to the second trick. When you see clearly the bad things that are likely to happen you will look harder for a remedy. When confronted with a hand such as this many beginning (or careless) players just automatically start trying to pull trumps. And many times they go down on hands that could have been made.}
[Play "W"]SK

